    <!-- 1. Polynomial kernel -->
    <h3>Polynomial kernel</h3>
    <p>A kernel k(x,y) computes the inner product in a feature space without explicitly mapping there. The polynomial kernel k(x,y) = (x&middot;y + c)<sup>d</sup> implicitly maps to all monomials up to degree d. Higher degree means a more flexible decision boundary.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Polynomial kernel: k(x,y) = (dot(x,y) + c)^d
; For d=2, this implicitly maps to a space
; containing all degree-2 monomials

(define (dot xs ys)
  (let loop ((xs xs) (ys ys) (sum 0))
    (if (null? xs) sum
        (loop (cdr xs) (cdr ys)
              (+ sum (* (car xs) (car ys)))))))

(define (poly-kernel x y c d)
  (expt (+ (dot x y) c) d))

; Two 2D points
(define x1 (list 1 2))
(define x2 (list 3 4))

(display "linear (d=1): ")
(display (poly-kernel x1 x2 1 1)) (newline)

(display "quadratic (d=2): ")
(display (poly-kernel x1 x2 1 2)) (newline)

(display "cubic (d=3): ")
(display (poly-kernel x1 x2 1 3))
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Polynomial kernel: k(x,y) = (dot(x,y) + c)^d
import math

def dot(xs, ys):
    return sum(a*b for a,b in zip(xs, ys))

def poly_kernel(x, y, c=1, d=2):
    return (dot(x, y) + c) ** d

x1 = [1, 2]
x2 = [3, 4]
for d in [1, 2, 3]:
    print("d={}: {}".format(d, poly_kernel(x1, x2, c=1, d=d)))
`} />
    </div>


    <!-- 2. RBF kernel -->
    <h3>RBF kernel</h3>
    <p>The radial basis function (RBF) kernel k(x,y) = exp(-gamma * ||x-y||<sup>2</sup>) maps to an infinite-dimensional space. It measures similarity: nearby points get kernel values close to 1, distant points approach 0. The parameter gamma controls the width of the Gaussian bump.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; RBF kernel: k(x,y) = exp(-gamma * ||x-y||^2)

(define (sq-dist xs ys)
  (let loop ((xs xs) (ys ys) (sum 0))
    (if (null? xs) sum
        (loop (cdr xs) (cdr ys)
              (+ sum (expt (- (car xs) (car ys)) 2))))))

(define (rbf-kernel x y gamma)
  (exp (* (- gamma) (sq-dist x y))))

(define a (list 0 0))
(define b (list 1 0))
(define c (list 5 5))

(define gamma 0.5)

(display "k(a,a) = ")
(display (rbf-kernel a a gamma)) (newline)  ; 1.0

(display "k(a,b) = ")
(display (/ (round (* (rbf-kernel a b gamma) 10000)) 10000)) (newline)

(display "k(a,c) = ")
(display (/ (round (* (rbf-kernel a c gamma) 10000)) 10000))
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`import math

def rbf_kernel(x, y, gamma=0.5):
    sq_dist = sum((a-b)**2 for a,b in zip(x, y))
    return math.exp(-gamma * sq_dist)

a = [0, 0]
b = [1, 0]
c = [5, 5]
print("k(a,a) = {:.4f}".format(rbf_kernel(a, a)))  # 1.0
print("k(a,b) = {:.4f}".format(rbf_kernel(a, b)))
print("k(a,c) = {:.4f}".format(rbf_kernel(a, c)))
`} />
    </div>


    <!-- 3. SVM decision boundary -->
    <h3>SVM decision boundary via kernel</h3>
    <p>The SVM decision function is f(x) = sign(sum of alpha_i * y_i * k(x_i, x) + b), where the sum runs over support vectors. Only a few training points (the support vectors) determine the boundary. This is classification without ever computing coordinates in feature space.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Toy SVM: classify using support vectors + RBF kernel
; Pre-trained alphas and bias for XOR-like data

(define (rbf x y gamma)
  (exp (* (- gamma)
          (+ (expt (- (car x) (car y)) 2)
             (expt (- (cadr x) (cadr y)) 2)))))

; Support vectors, labels, alphas (pretrained)
(define svs   (list (list 0 0) (list 1 1) (list 0 1) (list 1 0)))
(define labels (list -1 -1 1 1))
(define alphas (list 1.0 1.0 1.0 1.0))
(define bias 0.0)
(define gamma 2.0)

(define (svm-predict x)
  (let loop ((sv svs) (lb labels) (al alphas) (sum bias))
    (if (null? sv) (if (>= sum 0) 1 -1)
        (loop (cdr sv) (cdr lb) (cdr al)
              (+ sum (* (car al) (car lb)
                        (rbf x (car sv) gamma)))))))

(display "predict (0,0): ") (display (svm-predict (list 0 0))) (newline)
(display "predict (1,1): ") (display (svm-predict (list 1 1))) (newline)
(display "predict (0,1): ") (display (svm-predict (list 0 1))) (newline)
(display "predict (1,0): ") (display (svm-predict (list 1 0)))
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`import math

def rbf(x, y, gamma=2.0):
    return math.exp(-gamma * sum((a-b)**2 for a,b in zip(x, y)))

# Pre-trained SVM for XOR-like data
svs    = [[0,0], [1,1], [0,1], [1,0]]
labels = [-1, -1, 1, 1]
alphas = [1.0, 1.0, 1.0, 1.0]
bias   = 0.0

def svm_predict(x):
    s = bias
    for sv, y, a in zip(svs, labels, alphas):
        s += a * y * rbf(x, sv)
    return 1 if s >= 0 else -1

for pt in [[0,0], [1,1], [0,1], [1,0]]:
    print("predict {}: {}".format(pt, svm_predict(pt)))
`} />
    </div>


